metadata.name: Geode #45
metadata.description:
A single seed shape is chosen from 13, and placed onto the plane. At every step, a copy of this seed is laid edge-to-edge adjacent to an existing shape, without causing any overlaps. This copy is colored based on the edge it shares with the existing shape. The process continues until the animation completes.

New shapes are placed closest to a moving target. In some mints, this target is slow moving, causing new shapes to expand radially from the seed. In other mints, this target races around, causing new shapes to chase it. 

Each of the 13 shapes forms different patterns under different circumstances. Not all patterns will be explored.

Controls:
  - SPACE: Pause/unpause the animation.
  - ENTER: Skip the animation.
  - R: Restart the animation.

URL Params:
  - "preview=1": Skip the animation.
  - "flex=1": Adapt the boundaries to the size of the window.
  - “slow=1”: Draw only one shape per frame.

metadata.name: Décollage #138
metadata.description:
A generative sketch based on the concept of décollage, an artistic process that involves cutting or tearing pieces of an original image. The resulting outputs bear a resemblance to artworks produced using the lacerated poster technique, where posters are layered and torn to reveal parts of the posters underneath.

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels. Note that this will not work with sizes beyond 5000 pixels.

(Allowlist is based on quantity of previous works owned).

metadata.name: Element #139
metadata.description:
Element is a generative series of pixelated mosaics that explores two contrasting styles of generative art. One style embraces imperfection and noise to simulate paint or other real-life textures, while the other produces digital outputs with precise forms.

The mosaics were inspired by the works of Hiroshi Kawano, one of the pioneers of generative art. They are generated by randomly placing rectangles inside a grid then applying a Markov-chain process multiple times. A hand-drawn and organic style is then incorporated using various techniques such drawing many rectangles with subtle variations in colour for a paint texture or adding different kinds of noise.

Please view in full-screen for the best experience.

Press [s] when the output is fully rendered to download it as a png file. The resolution can be set by adding for example "&s=2048" to the url for a 2048 x 2048 output.

Element was released as part of the Cure3 exhibition, generating vital funds for Cure Parkinson's medical research.

metadata.name: Hello World #142
metadata.description:
With this token, I am entering a new chapter in making generative art. 

I recorded myself saying "Hello World" and converted the sound file to a set of amplitudes extracted from my voice. That set of amplitudes was then used to create a rotating set of discs that are orbiting a "Sun". 

As the system is rotating, the details of a generative overlay can be seen more clearly. This overlay is also a sneak peak into my next artwork coming soon.

Press keys 1-4 to change the view, press "F" to toggle framerate between 60 and 30.

metadata.name: Skravert #102
metadata.description:
‘Skravert’ - Norwegian, verb, past tense. ‘The act of filling an area with lines; to shade an area’.

Skravert is a series of 320 sketches, each capturing the texture and feel of a material residing somewhere between cardboard and woolen rugs. The project is centred around rectangle subdivision and a line drawing algorithm, giving each piece its own unique expression when combined with a selection of 28 different color  palettes.  

Original artwork by perkwerk * made with p5.js * 2021

metadata.name: Espacios comunes #38
metadata.description:
At moment we decide to draw a square on top of a circle, we are defining a time arrow, a third dimension on the 2D plane, where shapes can be on o top of each other, come one after the other. In this project i wanted to remove that time arrow, that third dimension, and leave the 2D plane as flat as possible.

Shapes are not drawn in sequence, they are formed by the continuous addition of points to each region defined by the shapes intersections. Not a single region is on top of the other. They are the result of the combination of shapes, and defined by them. Horizontal, decentralized societies. Espacios comunes. We can see the circles, squares, plane cuts, but we cannot give them an order or authority.

-----

Key controls:

- UP arrow: Increases the sketch resolution. It will take longer to render but it will produce better quality images.
- DOWN arrow: Decreases the sketch resolution.
- f: Removes or adds an empty frame around the image.
- d: Increases the points density. More points will be painted and regions will become more full.
- n: Increases the pixel noise.
- b: Decreases the pixel noise.
- z: Switches on and off the simple pixel sorting algorithm. Move the mouse left and right to change the pixel stickiness.
- x: Switches on and off a more complex version of the pixel sorting algorithm.
- i: Displays some log information.
- p: Pauses the sketch.
- s: Saves a screenshot of the artwork. The image resolution will depend on the sketch resolution, which is controlled by the UP and DOWN arrows.

-----

URL controls:

width=2000 will set the sketch width to 2000 pixels.
proportion=2.3 will set the sketch width-to-height ratio to 2.3.
You can combine these two parameters to create any image output you want. For example, to create an image that is 3000 pixels wide and 5000 pixels high, one just needs to add &width=3000&proportion=0.6 to the URL.

-----

Special thanks to @andregorayeb (Gora) and @ItonkStudio (Itonk) for letting me use some of their color palettes for this project.

-----

metadata.name: The Slow Climb #180
metadata.description:
The quickest path to the top can be seen only after reaching the top. Following any other path, no doubt will take longer and will be more difficult.

The path you chose to take may not be straight, it may be full of obstacles, it may even seem impossible to continue at times. Add to that, you have no idea how long more it will take. It is also possible that this path may not lead you to the top.

What is certain is that if you stop climbing just now, you will never reach the top.

So, will you keep climbing or stop and go back?

* * *

S: Save PNG
D: Hide dents

To save a larger image, open live view, add "&s=WIDTH_IN_PIXELS" to the end of the URL, press Enter and then press S.

Chrome is recommended for faster rendering.

Artwork by: yenren / twitter.com/yenrenART
